<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Lobbying on home loans is renewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mortgage lenders are to renew their lobbying of ministers and MPs after
signs that the government is considering further cuts in the income support
available for mortgage interest, Alison Smith writes.
The Council of Mortgage Lenders, which represents building societies, banks
and centralised lenders, is to brief backbench Tory MPs about the likely
adverse impact of further restrictions on the fragile recovery in the
housing market. The arguments against a further limitation will also form a
significant element of the council's submission to the Treasury before
November's Budget. At least one building society chief executive believes
lenders should have concentrated more on preventing the reduction of
mortgage support than on opposing the cuts in tax relief on mortgage
interest payments.
While the Pounds 1.2bn spending on mortgage support last year is not a large
slice of the Pounds 85bn social security budget, ministers believe it is
among the fastest-growing elements. They are keen to encourage people to
take out private insurance against job loss rather than relying on the state
to help with mortgage payments if they become unemployed. Last August, a
ceiling of Pounds 150,000 was im-posed on the mortgage amount for which
income support would be available. This was lowered to Pounds 125,000 for
new claimants from early this month. A further restriction will come into
effect later this month when people on income support will no longer be able
to claim interest payments on mortgages which they have taken out or
increased while receiving benefit.
But the council believes that imposing tougher limits on mortgage support
payments will directly cut across the government's intention of extending
home ownership through initiatives such as the rents-into-mortgages scheme.
The original crackdown on support came after embarrassment over a case in
which amounts of almost Pounds 2,000 a week were paid to a former insurance
sales executive.
Mortgage surge, Page 10
</TEXT>
