<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Planning at Westminster council to be probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Westminster City Council is launching an independent review of whether its
proposed Unitary Development Plan could have been drawn up as part of a
gerrymandering exercise related to controversial sales of council houses.
The launch of the inquiry is the nearest the Conservative-controlled council
has come to admitting that the alleged gerrymandering exercise - supposedly
planned to boost Tory votes in eight marginal wards - may have extended
beyond council house sales to other activities, including the planning
process. It puts a question mark over Westminster's policies on the eve of
the local elections.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, yesterday said that the Westminster
Conservatives, who have a slim majority, deserve to be re-elected.
Mr John Magill, the district auditor, this year made a preliminary ruling
that the 'designated sales' of council houses in the late 1980s were
unlawful and recommended that 10 councillors and officers, including the
then leader, Dame Shirley Porter, should be surcharged Pounds 21.5m.
According to draft terms of reference of the inquiry, the review will be
carried out by an unspecified independent person because 'it has been
suggested that the director of planning and environment (Mr Syd Sporle) may
have been involved in the alleged improper regard to electoral advantage
(sic)'.
The review of the development plan follows assessments of its legality by
three QCs, two working for the council and one employed by the opposition
Labour group.
The review will focus on allegations by Labour's deputy leader in
Westminster, Mr Peter Bradley, that the development plan was 'decisively
influenced' by the Conservative party strategy called Building Stable
Communities. The strategy's alleged aim was to focus council resources
between 1987 and 1990 on boosting the Conservative vote.
The auditor has made a provisional ruling that the policy of removing 500
council properties a year from public ownership was designed with the aim of
increasing owner-occupancy in the eight marginal wards for political
purposes and at the price of failing to fulfil obligations to the homeless
and other priority housing groups. Mr Bradley has alleged that the Unitary
Development Plan, based on 1988 revisions to the district plan, was drawn up
with the same intention.
The draft terms of reference say the inquiry will look at three aspects of
the development plan:
The alleged deletion of any reference to the provision of council housing or
low-rent housing association accommodation, because any such reference could
have undermined the policy of selling council houses.
The inclusion of a clause that 'planning permission will normally be granted
for the change of use of hostels to residential use where the hostel is
surplus to the requirements of the institution or body which uses it'. Mr
Bradley alleges that this has already been used to justify planning consent
granted in connection with the eviction of residents from a hostel by
Westminster Cathedral.
An allegation that the policy on redevelopment of industrial mews is
intended to allow consent to be granted for high-cost residential
conversions for private-sector sale.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
