<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Friendly society woos life company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Family Assurance friendly society plans to buy Templeton Life Assurance,
part of the Templeton Marketing Group, for Pounds 1.75m.
This is the first time a friendly society has tried to acquire a life
assurance company and is a sign of the changing financial services
marketplace.
Family Assurance, based in Brighton, says it wishes to acquire Templeton
Life for its pensions expertise. Templeton Life, which has Pounds 230m under
management, markets and underwrites life assurance and pension policies.
The acquisition on July 1 depends on Family Assurance members' agreement and
approval by the Friendly Societies' Commission.
Mr John Reeve, Family Assurance chief executive, said the acquisition would
place the society in a stronger position in the personal-pensions market. He
said: 'Our long-term aim is to be the country's most dominant provider of
tax-exempt savings and this acquisition is an important step nearer that
goal.'
The acquisition would add 32,000 policyholders to Family Assurance's 500,000
members and would bring its assets under management to just under Pounds
1bn. This would place it close to the second-largest friendly society, Royal
Liver Assurance, which has more than Pounds 1bn under management.
Templeton Life arose from the de-mutualisation in 1990 of Time Assurance
company, another friendly society. The company has found it hard to sell its
products through independent financial advisers, its main sales outlet in an
increasingly competitive market.
Friendly societies grew from the co-operative movement, providing protection
for workers against sickness and unemployment. Investment by individuals in
societies' tax-free savings schemes is limited to Pounds 200 a year.
</TEXT>
