<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 94 / Italian prices edge upward
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Rome
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italian consumer prices grew 0.3 per cent in April giving an annualised
inflation rate of 4.1 per cent. The monthly rate was marginally up on March
largely due to a rise in cigarette prices. But so far this year the biggest
single rises have been in housing and health. The rise in housing costs in
particular has almost doubled the index average. The prospective rate for
the year as a whole is now running at 4 per cent against 4.2 per cent for
1993. The outgoing government hoped to have a year-end inflation rate
running at an annualised 3.5 per cent. Economists indicated yesterday that
the new government would inherit inflation rates still relatively high by EU
standards and this made cautious management of Italy's timid recovery
essential.
</TEXT>
