<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Equity Markets: Investors wary ahead of April jobs data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
This week's calendar is dotted with important economic readings, culminating
with Friday's report on April employment trends.
With the Federal Reserve in the process of tightening monetary policy, and
its next move to higher interest rates expected any day, the mood is wary.
However, it is even more difficult than usual to forecast the direction
share prices will take as Friday approaches.
Yesterday's action revealed the market's mercurial bent. Cyclical stocks
finished with solid gains, despite the flat reaction during the morning to a
seemingly favourable report from the National Association of Purchasing
Management. The NAPM's April survey showed the industrial sector continued
to grow at a healthy pace in April, while prices were rising at more
moderate rate than in the previous two months.
'Greenspan (the Fed chairman) told us basically in February to watch for any
scrap of inflation information we can find, so that's what we are doing,'
says Mr Donald Straszheim, of Merrill Lynch in New York. Looking ahead to
the employment data, Mr Straszheim is forecasting that payrolls increased by
140,000 in April, a gain consistent with second-quarter economic growth of
about 4 per cent.
At first glance, the financial markets certainly seem inclined to accentuate
the negative. Last Thursday, bonds were battered on the announcement that
gross domestic product had grown at weaker-than-expected 2.6 per cent in the
first quarter. Investors apparently suspected that the economy had
accelerated as soon as the harsh winter weather lifted.
Two worrying inflation readings included in the GDP report also weighed
heavily in the fixed-income markets. 'The inflation figures scared people
and so they figured the Fed is going to lean even heavier on the brakes and
abort the recovery,' says Mr Alfred Goldman, of AG Edwards in St Louis.
Spooked by the prospect of tighter money, equity investors ran scared.
Or did they? Sure, the Dow industrials fell 31 points on the day, but the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was only marginally lower. 'In my
opinion, stocks handled a very weak bond market very well,' says Mr Don
Hays, of Wheat First Butcher &amp; Singer in Norfolk.
He characterises the session as 'neutral', pointing out that each successive
sell-off since February's shift in monetary policy has been milder than the
previous one.
Mr Hays expects another steep decline in the next two or three weeks,
probably when the Fed decides to tighten again. 'That will be the next
little test of the market,' he says. But in the middle term, the analyst is
bullish, predicting a big upturn soon after the Fed's next policy-making
session on May 17.
Mr Goldman holds much the same view. 'I'm looking for three or four more
weeks of backing and filling - up a little, down a little - but basically
building a base for an interim rally going into the summer,' he says.
</TEXT>
