<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Credit card use points to squeeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax and National Insurance increases may already have significantly
depressed spending, according to figures from Barclaycard, which has the
largest share of the UK credit card market.
While any impact since the increase in deductions has yet to show through in
discretionary spending, the amounts spent since the Budget on November 30
have fallen.
Figures for Barclaycard's weekly sales turnover last summer show that
spending using the credit card was running at about 12 per cent higher than
during the same months in 1992.
From December, however, the percentage increase in turnover for each month
against the comparable period the previous year dropped to 6 per cent to 8
per cent.
The amounts processed by Barclaycard on any given day - which reflect
spending in the day or so immediately before - suggest a slight drop when
last week is compared with its equivalent last year.
At the start of the week, spending was about 120 per cent of the 1993 value,
while by Thursday's figures it had slipped to 110 per cent of last year's
figure.
