<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Government urged to press for curb on Brussels' power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An influential think-tank today urges the government to press its case for a
more decentralised European Union by proposing a radical plan to curb the
powers of the European Commission.
The European Policy Forum says the present powers of the commission should
be divided between three new institutions: a commission for the single
market; a treasury board responsible for all spending and revenue decisions;
and a new external trade commission.
The forum argues that this 'unbundling' of the commission's powers could be
a central element in the reform of the union at the Intergovernmental
Conference due in 1996.
Alongside plans to transfer greater control over financial affairs and the
single market to the council of ministers it would reverse the momentum
towards the centralisation of decision-making in the EU.
The forum is an independent group with cross-party support. But its latest
paper, written by Mr Frank Vibert, the director, is likely to attract
widespread support on the Tory backbenches.
Its effect would be to repatriate to member governments much of the
influence over the political and economic direction of the union by casting
the commission in an essentially managerial role. Its involvement in the
union's foreign and security policy and in home affairs would be transferred
to the secretariat of the Council of Ministers.
Mr Vibert argues that at present the commission gives too little prominence
to the single market while its spending reflexes have always overwhelmed its
sense of responsibility for financial discipline.
A three-way division of its authority would restore the focus on ensuring
European competitiveness. At the same time the forum suggests that the
commission's quasi-judicial functions would be transferred to an independent
competition authority modelled on Germany's Bundeskartellemt.
The paper coincides with a call from the Institute of Community Studies, a
sociological research group, for co-ordinated Europe-wide cuts in VAT as
part of a package of policies to stop the EU 'imploding' under the weight of
mounting unemployment. The study argues that record unemployment will
permanently derail European integration without 'rigorous and co-ordinated
action' from member states.
The Future Role of the European Commission. EPF, 20 Queen Anne's Gate,
London SW1H 9AA. Pounds 7.50. Europe isn't Working. Institute of Community
Studies, 18 Victoria Park Sq, London E2 9PF. Pounds 9.95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
