FT  03 MAY 94 / Tory election leaflet sparks row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday accused the Tories of making false claims in the
Dudley, West Midlands, local election campaign, breaching the Representation
of the People Act, Paul Cheeseright writes.
The row, in a so far tepid campaign where Labour is seeking to hold on to a
two-seat majority, erupted in the Amblecote ward, where Labour won a seat by
a handful of votes in 1990.
A campaign leaflet sent out by Mr John Martin, the Tory candidate, and
published by Mr Colin Banks, his agent, reprinted an article from The Sun
newspaper which alleged that three Labour councillors had planned to visit
New Delhi and study the Indian Fire Brigade. A Labour official said last
night that 'never had any such trip been planned whatsoever'.
A letter to Mr Banks from Mr Fraser Kemp, Labour's west Midlands organiser,
demanded a retraction, a public apology and threatened to pass the whole
matter to the director of public prosecutions.
Mr Banks commented that the leaflet had touched 'a raw nerve'.
