<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Profit-pay benefits on tax 'abused'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Profit-related pay has become part of the tax avoidance industry and its tax
benefits have been abused, says a report by the Institute of Employment
Rights, Richard Donkin writes.
The study joins a growing chorus of disillusionment with PRP as a means of
rewarding employees. Its author Ms Hazel McLean, a Cambridge University law
lecturer, says that PRP has failed to motivate employees or make labour
costs more flexible by varying with levels of profitability as its
proponents had claimed.
Ms McLean says recent legislation on PRP and employee share option schemes
has done nothing to encourage economic or industrial democracy. She says she
has found little evidence that it has either encouraged identification of
employees with their companies or provided incentives for employees to
increase company profits - two of the main principles behind its origin.
Companies are becoming more open in their accounts about how they pay their
directors and what directors' share options are worth, says Company
Reporting, the Edinburgh-based monthly accounts monitor.
The May issue says that the growing mood among companies to be open about
links between directors' pay and future performance, shows that pressure
from institutional investors and the Cadbury committee, which last year made
recommendations for complete information on directors' remuneration, is
paying off.
</TEXT>
