<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Labour vows to combat City 'short-termism'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Labour government would seek to reform companies law to counter the
culture of City 'short-termism' which the party believes is harming
industry.
A 17,000-word paper on competitiveness, to be published next week, will set
out a six-point plan for reviving industry, including tougher controls on
takeovers and a network of development agencies to promote economic activity
in the regions.
The timing of the launch is designed to steal some of the thunder from the
government's much-trumpeted competitiveness white paper, due for publication
on May 16.
It follows last week's report by the Tory-controlled Commons trade and
industry committee, which urged institutional investors to adopt a more
flexible approach to corporate dividend payments and singled out City
short-termism as a structural weakness damaging Britain's prospects.
The white paper - set to appear in the critical period between the
approaching local and European elections - is expected to act as a mid-term
manifesto, pulling together a range of policies on education, training and
manufacturing.
News of the Labour document emerged as Mr John Smith, party leader, promised
an audience of trade unionists a 'new deal for working people', enshrining
'proper' rights in the workplace and a statutory national minimum wage. Mr
Smith, addressing the annual conference in Blackpool of the shopworkers'
union Usdaw, did not give a precise figure at which the minimum would be
pitched. He said only that rates of less than Pounds 3 an hour were judged
to be too generous by the government.
Underlining Labour's commitment to the goal of full employment, Mr Smith
promised action to ensure that employers could not deny union representation
to workers who voted in favour of it in a secret ballot.
He also pledged that signing the social chapter of the Maastricht treaty
would be among the first acts of the next Labour government.
Next week's paper will back the imposition of statutory interest payments on
companies which settle their debts late - a move under consideration by
ministers - and urge that companies which attempt hostile takeovers should
have to prove the deal would be in the public interest.
Focusing on the need to encourage more long-term investment in
manufacturing, it will argue that the fear of a takeover is the single
largest reason why the dividends paid by UK companies are comparatively
high.
</TEXT>
