<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Jury convicts Virani of BCCI fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Nazmudin Virani, the former property entrepreneur, was convicted at the
Old Bailey yesterday of seven counts of fraud relating to his business
dealings with the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
The jury found Mr Virani guilty on one count of false accounting and six of
furnishing false information to Price Waterhouse, the BCCI auditors, in
order to help artificially boost the bank's profits by about Pounds 11m.
Mr Virani will be sentenced on May 11. However, concern he might abscond led
the judge to refuse bail and order him to be remanded in custody.
Mr Justice Hutchison warned Mr Virani that the offences of which he had been
convicted were sufficiently serious that a prison sentence 'appears
inevitable'. The charges carry a maximum term of seven years' imprisonment.
The conviction marks the third successful prosecution for the Serious Fraud
Office over the BCCI scandal. Mr Syed Ali Akbar, a former head of BCCI's
treasury division, and Mr Mohammed Baqi, a former head of Attock Oil, a
company owned by BCCI, have already been convicted after the SFO's
investigation.
The jury acquitted Mr Virani on single charges of conspiracy to defraud,
theft and furnishing false information. It was unable to reach verdicts on a
further four counts of furnishing false information. These charges will not
now be proceeded with.
At the heart of the fraud committed by Mr Virani was what the prosecution
described as a 'you scratch my back and I'll scratch yours' relationship
with Mr Mohammed Haque, the head of BCCI's property division, who fled to
Pakistan.
As BCCI's financial troubles deepened in the late 1980s, Mr Virani signed a
series of bogus audit confirmations which misled the auditors and inflated
the bank's profits.
In return, BCCI gave Mr Virani cash payments totalling Pounds 1.6m and
played a substantial role in the expansion of Control Securities, the
property company Mr Virani headed from 1985 until his arrest.
Mr Virani's conviction ends a meteoric business career which began after he
was expelled from Uganda in 1972 by President Idi Amin. The growth of the
Virani Group property empire and his stewardship of Control Securities were
two successes that led to his being named Asian businessman of the year in
1990.
</TEXT>
