<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Fears increase for further Bosnian flashpoint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb leader, yesterday vowed that he would
block any moves to designate as a United Nations 'safe area' the town of
Brcko, on the eastern end of the Serb corridor in Bosnia.
The 'corridor is of vital interest to the Serbian nation', he said, ruling
out any possible change in the status of Brcko, which has 'always been in
Serb hands'.
Earlier, Mr Alain Juppe, French foreign minister, had called on the UN to
make the Brcko corridor 'a security zone' with the same status as Sarajevo
or Gorazde, so that Nato aircraft could intervene 'at the first cannon shot
. . . by one side or the other'.
Speaking to the Anglo-American Press Association in Paris, Mr Juppe
described the Brcko corridor as 'very sensitive' to both Moslems, who wanted
it for access to the Sava river and thence to the Danube, and to Serbs, who
wanted it to link their territories in east and west Bosnia.
UN officials fear the town will be the next flashpoint and are considering
how a conflict can be avoided.
In Gorazde, the Moslem enclave in south-east Bosnia, UN reports cite
heightened tensions, including an incident on Saturday in which British
soldiers returned fire, killing two Serbs. In a similar incident near Tuzla,
another UN 'safe area', nine Serbs were killed after firing four anti-tank
missiles at soldiers from the Nordic battalion who used their tanks in the
exchange.
There were further reports yesterday that Serb forces are concentrating
their heavy weapons in the strategic north-eastern region.
Mr Haris Silajdzic, Bosnian prime minister, who today is due to meet Mr
Yasushi Akashi, senior UN official for former Yugoslavia, in Sarajevo to
discuss resuming peace talks, yesterday warned that his government would not
rejoin negotiations until Serb forces complied fully with a Nato ultimatum
to withdraw from a 20 km zone around Gorazde.
UN officials said at the weekend that Serb soldiers had shed their army
fatigues only to return in blue uniforms in the guise of policemen
protecting Serb settlers. The immediate resettlement of Serbs is part of a
Serb plan to partition Gorazde.
In Sarajevo, Nato aircraft buzzed a weapons depot ending a four-hour
standoff between Serb forces trying to take back their heavy weapons from UN
soldiers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
