<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 94 / Scandal forces Gonzalez to cancel trip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Felipe Gonzalez, Spain's prime minister, yesterday cancelled an official
trip he was due to start today to Romania and Bulgaria because of the
growing political storm over corruption and illicit gains in the country.
Mr Antoni Asuncion, the interior minister, submitted his resignation at the
weekend in a move which reflected acute embarrassment in the socialist
government over the disappearance of Mr Luis Roldan, former head of the
paramilitary Civil Guard, wanted for questioning by an examining magistrate.
Mr Gonzalez postponed accepting Mr Asuncion's resignation, telling him to
step up the search for Mr Roldan. The Madrid daily newspaper El Mundo is
expected today to publish an interview with Mr Roldan at a secret location,
in which he threatens to make damaging revelations. Before he disappeared,
Mr Roldan said he would reveal information that would harm the Socialists.
The affair, along with allegations of tax evasion by Mr Mariano Rubio,
former Bank of Spain governor, increasingly risks jeopardising the future of
Mr Gonzalez's minority government.
Mr Jordi Pujol, leader of the Catalan nationalist party on which the
Socialists depend for a parliamentary majority, raised the possibility of a
snap election if Mr Gonzalez fails to bring the situation under control. The
conservative opposition Popular party has issued fresh calls for Mr Gonzalez
to resign.
Mr Asuncion, a former director of prisons, was appointed only five months
ago. His predecessor, Mr Jose Luis Corcuera, resigned when a law including
new search powers was ruled unconstitutional. The latter has also come under
attack because of the Roldan affair.
Hundreds of police and army personnel are engaged in the search for Mr
Roldan, who faces arrest over alleged tax and other offences. A
parliamentary committee has heard evidence that he received millions of
dollars in commissions for building works.
</TEXT>
