<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 94 / International Company News: German tool maker files for
protection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Deckel Maho, the German machine tool group, yesterday filed for protection
from its creditors just 12 months after it was formed through the merger of
two rival companies.
It gave up the struggle after one of its backers refused to take part in a
bank-led rescue package.
PSV, an incorporated industry association which guarantees member-companies'
pension schemes, said it would not take over responsibility for Deckel
Maho's total DM45m (Dollars 26.3m) pension commitments. It offered only to
pay current retirement benefits for three years.
The association, which represents more than 30,000 companies, said earlier
this week it had to consider possible future demands on its resources.
A life-saving package costing several hundred million D-Marks in written-off
debt and new capital, agreed between a banking consortium and Bavarian state
financial institutions, was conditional on PSV's full participa-tion.
Deutsche Bank, which together with the Bayerische Vereinsbank last year led
the supposed rescue-merger project, said yesterday it was trying to find a
constructive solution.
If Deckel Maho is allowed to collapse, this could bring problems for
Gildemeister which has a foreign distribution joint venture with the
troubled concern and which in the past has been named as a possible white
knight.
The group, which is reducing capacity and slimming its workforce from 1,800
to 1,200, made a net loss in the year to mid-1993 of DM45m on sales of
DM310m.
This week's crisis coincides with the first signs of recovery in the machine
tool business. Orders rose in the first quarter of this year for the first
time since 1991.
</TEXT>
