<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 94 / Books: A forestful of fantasies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHENA MACKAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EATING PAVLOVA by DM Thomas Bloomsbury Pounds 15.99, 231 pages
UNDER THE VULCANIA by Maureen Freely Bloomsbury Paperback Pounds 4.99, 139
pages
FISHING THE SLOE-BLACK RIVER by Colum McCann Phoenix House Pounds 13.99, 184
pages
Sigmund Freud died of cancer of the jaw in Hampstead in 1939. DM Thomas's
novel is in the form of a memoir supposedly written and dreamed by Freud in
his last morphine clouded days. He was nursed by his daughter Anna, the
renowned child psychoanalyst, then in her forties, and much of the book's
focus is on Anna, whose life was consumed by her father. This is not the
first time Thomas has used Freud in a novel; the 'father of psychoanalysis'
checked into the notorious White Hotel.
Eating Pavlova will annoy Freudians and confirm others in their prejudices
as Thomas, acting the ventriloquist, sits on his knee an old goat dummy
whose bleatings put a mediocre gloss on his life and work, and who exhibits
a mild fixation on corsets and suspenders. On page one the baby
Sigmund/Oedipus watches his parents making love and offers this beatitude:
'Happy is the infant whose father fills him with a passion for forests by
coupling with his bride in full view.'
Then there is a long section devoted to Freud re-falling in love with his
wife Martha in middle age, a period which provides the novelist with a
forestful of sexual fantasies, embellishment and lies. Historic figures,
including Jung, HD Bryher and Helene Deutsch troop through the narrative and
Pavlova dances past in a memory inspired by a dream of her pudding, that
confection of meringue and fruit which can so easily collapse into
sogginess.
The text is interspersed with fictional hindsight and genuine case histories
and a story 'written' by Anna, in which she is married to her father. The
final scene is touching as Freud, now a guilty ghost, foresees Anna old and
alone in the house where she lived on until 1982, and which is now the Freud
Museum, but it is tempting to paraphrase another author's title into 'Eating
Pavlova is Wrong'.
'What do women want?' asks the ersatz Freud in the course of his adventures.
The women in Maureen Freely's Under the Vulcania want diversion from
unsatisfactory lives and marriages. The Vulcania is a pleasure dome devoted
to fulfilling their wildest fantasies. The Hard-On Cafe and the Merry-Go-
Vibrator might promise paradise at first, but Freely introduces subtly the
nightmarish potential of her palace of varieties staffed by Californian
Chippendales. Much of Freely's work, as novelist and journalist, is
concerned with balancing motherhood and sexual fulfilment, and here she
juggles desire and danger in a tight, astute, depressing and sometimes very
funny narrative.
Colum McCann is a young writer who has been hailed as part of the talented
new wave coming out of Ireland. Fishing the Sloe-Black River, his first
collection of stories, shows a poetic and angry observer taking the
well-worn path from Ireland to America. As with some of his compatriots, the
cadences of Irish speech and expressions add natural poetry to the prose and
these stories of exile and loss may possibly have been influenced by the
work of Desmond Hogan.
McCann's dispossessed characters, working in mental hospitals, dying of
Aids, seeking long lost sisters, are informed by a literariness and myth.
The souls of the dead of both sides of the conflict in Ireland turn into
swans in Cathal's lake, one of the less successful stories, where an old
farmer's rage and pity are patently the author's rather than his own. When
McCann eschews magic realism a credible compassion illuminates the squalor,
nastiness, brutality and beauty of modern life.
</TEXT>
<XX>
